.\" Manpage for _printf
.TH _PRINTF 3 "27 Nov 2025" "Version 1.1" "Custom C library"
.SH NAME
_printf \- prints formatted output to standard output

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "#include \"main.h\""
.br
.B int _printf(const char *format, ...);

.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf
function partially replicates the behavior of the standard
.B printf
function.
It prints a string of characters to standard output, supporting a limited set of format specifiers.

The supported format specifiers are:

.TP
.B "%c"
Prints a single character.
.TP
.B "%s"
Prints a string of characters.
.TP
.B "%d"
Prints a signed decimal integer.
.TP
.B "%i"
Prints a signed decimal integer.
.TP
.B "%%"
Prints the percent character '%'.
.B "%x"
Prints an unsigned integer in lowercase hexadecimal (base 16).
.TP
.B "%X"
Prints an unsigned integer in uppercase hexadecimal (base 16).
.TP
.B "%u"
Prints an unsigned decimal integer.
.TP
.B "%o"
Prints an unsigned integer in octal (base 8).
.TP
.B "%p"
Prints a pointer address in hexadecimal format, typically prefixed with "0x".

All other characters in the
.B format
string are printed as-is.

.SH PARAMETERS
.IP format
A string containing the text to print, including optional format specifiers.
.IP ...
Arguments corresponding to the format specifiers in the format string.

.SH RETURN VALUE
Returns the total number of characters printed to standard output.

.SH ERRORS
If an unsupported format specifier is encountered, the function prints '%' followed by the unknown character.
If
.B format
is
.RI NULL ,
the behavior is undefined.

.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
_printf("Char: %c, Name: %s, Dec: %d, Hex: %x, Oct: %o, Ptr: %p, %%\n", 'E', "Daniel", 63, 255, 255, &format);
.nf
Outputs something like:
Char: E, Name: Daniel, Dec: 63q, Hex: ff, Oct: 377, Ptr: 0x7ffee4c2a8f0, %
.fi

.SH NOTES
- Internal helper functions typically include
.B print_char,
.B print_string,
.B print_int,
.B print_unsigned,
.B print_hex,
.B print_octal
and
.B print_pointer.
.br
- Characters are printed one at a time using
.B _putchar.
.br
- Only the conversion specifiers listed above are supported.

